\begin_layout Section
Combinatorial estimates by the switching method 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HM10"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a finite set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 of objects.
 A switching is a (nondeterministic) operation that transforms one object
 into another (or more generally, a switching is a relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R\subseteq\Omega\times\Omega$
\end_inset

).
 We can partition 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 into subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ C\left(v\right)\right\} _{v\in V}$
\end_inset

 and put a directed graph structure (possibly with loops) on the index set
 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

: if an element in 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(v\right)$
\end_inset

 can switch to an element in 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(w\right)$
\end_inset

 then there is an arc between 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hopefully, for each 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 we can find a good lower bound 
\begin_inset Formula $a\left(v\right)$
\end_inset

 on the number of ways an 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in C\left(v\right)$
\end_inset

 can be switched, and a good upper bound 
\begin_inset Formula $b\left(v\right)$
\end_inset

 on the number of switchings an 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in C\left(v\right)$
\end_inset

 can be produced by.
 If we imagine that all switchings are performed at once, 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 give bounds on the inflow and outflow at each vertex in terms of the size
 of each 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(v\right)$
\end_inset

.
 (So, 
\begin_inset Formula $a\left(v\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b\left(v\right)$
\end_inset

 can more generally be bounds on the 
\shape italic
average
\shape default
 number of switchings per element in 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(v\right)$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This gives some information about the relative sizes of the classes 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(v\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Given a set of vertices 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $N\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

 be the total amount of elements in all 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 The objective of the paper is to bound 
\begin_inset Formula $N\left(Y\right)/N\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

 for given vertex sets 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to obtain bounds on 
\begin_inset Formula $N\left(Y\right)/N\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

, we write the constraints as a system of linear inequalities.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $s'\left(v,w\right)$
\end_inset

 be the (unknown) amount of switchings going from 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(v\right)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(w\right)$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, for any vertex 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum s'\left(vw\right)\ge a\left(v\right)N\left(v\right)$
\end_inset

.
 A nonzero assignment of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 satisfying the full set of inequalities is called a 
\shape italic
feasible solution
\shape default
, and a feasible solution which maximizes 
\begin_inset Formula $N\left(Y\right)/N\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

 is called an 
\shape italic
optimal solution
\shape default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The key result of the paper is to show that optimal solutions always take
 one of six standard forms.
 This is proved by a reduction of the inequalities to a linear program,
 and the fact that an optimal solution of a linear program always occurs
 at a vertex of the corresponding convex polytope.
 The analysis is amenable to a general bound 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 on the arcs of the digraph instead of the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

 (in that case we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\left(v,w\right)=b\left(w\right)/a\left(v\right)$
\end_inset

).
 Although
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 doesn't have a clear combinatorial interpretation, the paper suggests that
 different 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 may arise from richer information bounding the behaviour of the flow of
 switchings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a number of commonly-satisfied assumptions, the paper proves some alternativ
e bounds for 
\begin_inset Formula $N\left(Y\right)/N\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

 that are slightly looser but easier to apply.
 In particular, a common use case is that we have some statistic on the
 objects in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 and we believe that objects with a high value of that statistic make up
 a negligible fraction of all the objects in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

.
 We would then partition the objects according to our statistic, and design
 a switching that tends to decrease the statistic, but by no more than some
 fixed amount.
 We would choose 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to be the set of all vertices (partititions) and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 would be the set of all vertices (partitions) with a statistic value higher
 than some 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

