\begin_layout Subsubsection
Overview
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Stein's method is a technique for bounding the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

distance
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 between distributions in some metric of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $d\left(X,Z\right)=\sup_{h\in\mathcal{H}}\left|\mathbb{E}h\left(X\right)-\mathbb{E}h\left(Z\right)\right|$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 is a family of functions.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}=\left\{ 1_{\left(-\infty,x\right]}:x\in\mathbb{R}\right\} $
\end_inset

, then this measures the maximum distance between distribution functions
 (Kolmogorov metric).
 It's often possible to transfer bounds between different metrics, so it's
 worthwhile to define some auxilary metrics for which it's easier to apply
 Stein's method.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I think the motivations behind Stein's method are twofold.
 First, it gives a concrete bound of the kind not usually provided by asymptotic
 methods.
 Second, it can be used to give uniform convergence of probabilities, which
 is sometimes a necessary ingredient to asymptotic results where we allow
 things to vary (for example, proving something about 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{G}\left(n,p\right)$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The idea of Stein's method is that there is some characterizing operator
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 of a random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\mathcal{A}f\left(X\right)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 in some manageable family 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

, precisely when 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 has the distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 For example, if 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\sim\mathcal{N}\left(0,1\right)$
\end_inset

 then we can choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $f\mapsto\left(x\mapsto f'\left(x\right)-xf\left(x\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 as the set of bounded, continuously differentiable functions.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\sim\mbox{Po}\left(\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 then we can choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $f\mapsto\left(k\mapsto\lambda f\left(k+1\right)-kf\left(k\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 as the set of all bounded functions with bounded differences.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For all 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

, we can try to choose 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{h}$
\end_inset

 to solve (or approximately solve) the functional equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}f_{h}=h-\mathbb{E}hZ$
\end_inset

 (and adjust/refine 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 to include all such 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{h}$
\end_inset

).
 Then, 
\begin_inset Formula $d\left(X,Z\right)\le\sup_{f\in\mathcal{F}}\left|\mathbb{E}\mathcal{A}f\left(X\right)\right|$
\end_inset

.
 By the choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

, we hope that this bound is relatively sharp.
 Also, we also hope that bounding 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbb{E}\mathcal{A}f\left(X\right)\right|$
\end_inset

 is easier than directly bounding 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbb{E}h\left(X\right)-\mathbb{E}h\left(Z\right)\right|$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Size-Bias Coupling
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a nonnegative integrable random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, we say 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{s}$
\end_inset

 has the size-bias distribution with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 if for all 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $Xf\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

 is integrable, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\E\left[Xf\left(X\right)\right]=\E X\E f\left(X^{s}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 For example, if 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a Bernoulli random variable then we can choose 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{s}=1$
\end_inset

.
 The size-bias distribution always exists, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\d\left(\L X^{s}\right)\left(x\right)=\frac{x}{\E X}\d\left(\L X\right)\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

; that is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\L X^{s}\right)\left(A\right)=\E\left[X\I_{A}\circ X\right]/\E X$
\end_inset

.
 The size-bias distribution can be seen as weighting (biasing) the probability
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 taking some value 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 by the size of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The idea is that we can perturb a nonnegative random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{s}$
\end_inset

 in such a way that 
\begin_inset Formula $X-X^{s}$
\end_inset

 has low variance.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 has mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\E\left[X^{s}-X\right]=\frac{1}{\mu}\E\left[X^{2}\right]-\mu=\frac{\sigma^{2}}{\mu}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is approximately Poisson, then this is equal to 1, so if 
\begin_inset Formula $X-X^{s}$
\end_inset

 has low variance then 
\begin_inset Formula $\E\left[Xf\left(X\right)-\lambda f\left(X+1\right)\right]=\lambda\E\left[f\left(X^{s}\right)-f\left(X+1\right)\right]\approx0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the normal case, define 
\begin_inset Formula $W=\frac{X-\mu}{\sigma}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{s}-X$
\end_inset

 has low variance then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\E\left[Wf\left(W\right)\right] & =\frac{\mu}{\sigma}\E\left[f\left(\frac{X^{s}-\mu}{\sigma}\right)-f\left(\frac{X-\mu}{\sigma}\right)\right]\\
 & \approx\frac{\mu}{\sigma}\E\left[f'\left(X\right)\left(\frac{X^{s}-X}{\sigma}\right)\right]\\
 & \approx\frac{\mu}{\sigma^{2}}\E\left[f'\left(X\right)\right]\E\left[X^{s}-X\right]\\
 & =\E\left[f'\left(X\right)\right].
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Here's an often-useful description of the size-bias distribution of a sum
 of random variables: If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}=\left(X_{i}\right)_{i=1}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a sequence of random variables, define 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}^{\left(i\right)}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\d\left(\L\mathbf{X}^{\left(i\right)}\right)\left(\mathbf{x}\right)=\frac{x_{i}}{\E X_{i}}\d\left(\L\mathbf{X}\right)\left(\mathbf{x}\right)$
\end_inset

, so that for any 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\E\left[f\left(\mathbf{X}^{\left(i\right)}\right)\right]=\E\left[X_{i}f\left(\mathbf{X}\right)\right]/\E\left[X_{i}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\sum_{i=1}^{n}X_{i}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr\left(I=i\right)=\E\left[X_{i}\right]/\E\left[X\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\L X^{s}=\L\sum_{i=1}^{n}X_{i}^{\left(I\right)}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An interpretation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\d\left(\L\mathbf{X}^{\left(i\right)}\right)\left(\mathbf{x}\right)=\frac{x_{i}}{\E X_{i}}\d\left(\L\mathbf{X}\right)\left(\mathbf{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 for discrete random variables is that the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th component of 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\left(i\right)}$
\end_inset

 has the size-bias distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 and given 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}^{\left(i\right)}=x$
\end_inset

, the other components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}^{\left(i\right)}$
\end_inset

 have the distribution of the corresponding components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}$
\end_inset

, conditioned on 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}=x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In practice, we can often represent 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 as a sum of indicator variables (which have size-bias distribution 1),
 each representing some local property of an underlying space of combinatorial
 objects.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 might be the number of isolated vertices in a random graph 
\begin_inset Formula $G\in\GBin np$
\end_inset

, so we would have an indicator for each vertex.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 we choose a location at random and force the local property to hold there;
 this creates a new object 
\begin_inset Formula $G'$
\end_inset

.
 Provided we have made the local adjustment in the right way, we will have
 
\begin_inset Formula $\L X\left(\cdot'\right)=\L X^{s}$
\end_inset

 in such a way that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is close to 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{s}$
\end_inset

.
 For the isolated vertex example, we can create 
\begin_inset Formula $G'$
\end_inset

 by deleting all the edges incident to a randomly chosen vertex.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Apparently, size-bias coupling is extensively used in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BHJ92"

\end_inset

, but not by name.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Exchangeable Pairs for Poisson Approximation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A pair of random variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(X,X'\right)$
\end_inset

 is exchangable if it has the same distribution as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(X',X\right)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(X,X'\right)$
\end_inset

 are exchangeable, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[1\left\{ X=X'+1\right\} f\left(X\right)\right]=\mathbb{E}\left[1\left\{ X'=X+1\right\} f\left(X'\right)\right]$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[\Pr\left(X'=X-1|X\right)f\left(X\right)\right]=\mathbb{E}\left[\Pr\left(X'=X+1|X\right)f\left(X+1\right)\right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So, if we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr\left(X'=X-1|X\right)\approx cX$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr\left(X'=X+1|X\right)\approx c\lambda$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[\lambda f\left(X\right)-Xf\left(X\right)\right]\approx0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is approximately Poisson.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To choose appropriate 
\begin_inset Formula $X'$
\end_inset

, we want to perturb 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 in some 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

reversible
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 way, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 can also be symmetrically viewed as a perturbation of 
\begin_inset Formula $X'$
\end_inset

.
 Sometimes 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 can be viewed as some statistic on a space 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 of combinatorial objects with some distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

, so we can obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $X'$
\end_inset

 with a reversible Markov chain on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 that has stationary distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, if 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a sum of indicator variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1},.\dots,X_{n}$
\end_inset

, we could view 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 as the cardinality of a random subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 1,\dots,n\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 For the transitions of a Markov chain, we could randomly select some 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\left\{ 1,\dots,n\right\} $
\end_inset

 and independently re-determine its membership.
 This sort of construction often naturally gives a suitable exchangeable
 pair.
 The event 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ X'=X-1\right\} $
\end_inset

 can be interpreted as a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

death
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and the event 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ X'=X+1\right\} $
\end_inset

 can be interpreted as an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

immigration
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the Markov chain.
 The probability of a death is roughly proportional to the number alive,
 and the probability of an immigration is roughly proportional to the sum
 of the probabilities for each element to be alive in the stationary distributio
n, which is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[X\right]\approx\lambda$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

