\end_inset

 from the set of antisymmetric functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
 Under some trivially satisfied conditions, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{im}T=\ker\E$
\end_inset

.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

characterizing operator
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\E$
\end_inset

.
 We then choose a connection operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha:\mathcal{F}_{0}\to\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With this data, Stein's lemma says that 
\begin_inset Formula $\E_{X}=\E_{0}+\E\circ R$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

remainder
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

